The paper deals with information theory and its applications to communication systems, specifically interference channels. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also involves the use of Lipschitz continuity and Wasserstein distance, which are topics in mathematical statistics and optimization, respectively. Therefore, cs.MS (Mathematical Statistics) and cs.SI (Systems and Control) are also likely sub-categories. The paper also uses transportation-information inequalities, which are related to probability theory and measure theory, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of outer bounds, which are related to machine learning and optimization, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category as well.
